model.

61
00:03:21,880 --> 00:03:23,760
Again I mentioned this briefly,

62
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:27,020
in the second week of the course just
recall that I talked a little bit

63
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:31,055
about hazard ratios In the context of the
concept of relative risk.

64
00:03:31,055 --> 00:03:33,460
It's yet another measure of relative risk.

65
00:03:33,460 --> 00:03:37,850
And it has a similar interpretation as
just a regular old basic rate ratio.

66
00:03:37,850 --> 00:03:40,640
It's the ratio of instantaneous incidence
rates, however.

67
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:42,780
So it's just slightly different from a
rate ratio.

68
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:45,120
It has to be calculated from regression.

69
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:47,400
You're not going to be able to calculate
it by hand.

70
00:03:47,400 --> 00:03:51,820
Since it comes from a regression, it's
